# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: center-fielder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:center-fielder/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He batted .300 five times, drove in 100 runs four times and had 13 seasons of 20 home runs.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] A strong base-runner early in his career, he also stole 30 bases three times.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He is one of eight MLB players with at least 300 home runs and 300 stolen bases during his career.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was a center fielder until knee problems – worsened by the artificial surface at Olympic Stadium – forced his shift to right field, followed by his move to a team which played on grass.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He led the NL in outfield putouts three consecutive years (1981–1983), and won eight Gold Glove Awards for fielding excellence.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was known for his incredible work ethic and study of the game.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He was often seen in the dugout with a clipboard in-hand documenting pitches and pitcher tendencies.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] This was long before such practices were common-place and such information was readily available.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Upon his retirement, his NL totals of 409 home runs and 962 extra base hits both ranked tenth in league history; he also ranked seventh in NL history in games as an outfielder (2,303), and sixth in both outfield putouts (5,116) and total chances (5,366).
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He set Expos franchise records for career games, at bats, runs scored, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, runs batted in, extra base hits, total bases, and steals, all of which have since been broken variously by Tim Raines, Tim Wallach and Vladimir Guerrero.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 2010, Dawson was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson grew up in Florida as the oldest of eight children.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] His father was a major general in the United States Army and often absent, leaving Dawson to look after his seven younger siblings while his mother worked.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson would pay his younger brothers in cookies to toss him rocks for him to hit with a broomstick as batting practice.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson's nickname, "The Hawk", was given to him by an uncle at a very early age.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson used to work out with a men's team that would hit him ground balls at practice.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson's uncle told him that most kids his age would shy away from the ball, but Dawson attacked the ball like a hawk.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson attended and graduated from Southwest Miami Senior High School in 1972.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In high school, he suffered multiple knee injuries which hampered his athletic development.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He did not draw any attention from professional scouts or college recruiters and took out student loans in order to enroll at Florida A&M University.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] At Florida A&M, Dawson walked on to the Rattlers baseball team as a freshman.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He spent three years at Florida A&M which he later said paved the way for his future.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was selected by the Expos in the 11th round (pick #250) of the 1975 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He played in 24 major league games in 1976 after making his debut on September 11.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] His stardom rose in 1977 when he became an everyday outfielder for the Expos, and batted .282 with 19 home runs and 21 stolen bases.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He was awarded the 1977 Rookie of the Year in the National League, narrowly beating out Steve Henderson of the New York Mets.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson had a blend of power and speed, hitting at least 20 home runs in seven seasons with the Expos, and stealing at least 20 bases in his first seven seasons.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson, playing primarily center field for the Expos, also became an excellent defensive player, gaining his first of eight Gold Glove Awards in 1980.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Based on his all-around excellence, Dawson was second in the National League MVP voting in 1981 (won by Mike Schmidt) and second again in 1983 (won by Dale Murphy).
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He was voted the Montreal Expos Player of the Year in 1981 and 1983.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson played 1,443 games with the Expos, fourth highest in franchise history, and set single-season club records for home runs (32, now seventh), RBI (113, now fourth), extra base hits (78, now seventh), and sacrifice flies (18, still first).
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He still holds the Expos career record for sacrifice flies (71), and is the only player to hit 200 home runs and steal 200 bases with Montreal.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] During his Expos days, Dawson hit two home runs in the same inning twice: at Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium against the Atlanta Braves on July 30, 1978 and at Wrigley Field against his future team, the Chicago Cubs, on September 24, 1985.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] As of 2021, Dawson, Willie McCovey, Jeff King, Alex Rodriguez, and Edwin Encarnación are the only five players to hit two home runs in one inning twice.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 1984, Dawson appeared in *The Cap*, a short film about a young boy living in Montreal who was given a baseball cap by Dawson.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson played for the Expos until after the 1986 season when he became a free agent and sought a team whose home field had natural grass, as his knee injuries were aggravated by Olympic Stadium's artificial turf.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] However, due to collusion on the part of the Major League Baseball owners, he was unable to attract offers.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] When the Cubs opened camp in Mesa, Arizona, that spring, Dawson and his agent Dick Moss arrived with a signed blank contract in an attempt to secure a contract with the Cubs.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson and Moss' stunt was derided as a "dog and pony show" by Green.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] The team also wrote in $100,000 bonuses if Dawson was MVP of either the league championship series or the World Series, but did not add a clause for National League MVP.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] While he won the NL MVP, the Cubs did not make the playoffs, so he had no chance to earn the NLCS or World Series MVP.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He became the Cubs' starting right fielder, and hit an MLB-leading 49 home runs (tied with Oakland Athletics rookie Mark McGwire), the most a player had hit since George Foster in 1977 and Willie Mays in 1965.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He was named the league's MVP, finally winning after the two years as runner-up in Montreal.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He also earned his fourth All-Star nod and won the Home Run Derby that year.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Although the Cubs held first place for nearly half of May and remained in contention through July, the team finished the 1987 season 76–85, last in the National League East.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was the first player to win a league MVP trophy from a last place team.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson played five more seasons with the Cubs, and was one of the franchise's most popular players during that time.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] His worst individual season came in 1989 when the Cubs won the National League East title.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] During the NL Championship Series that year, Dawson batted .105 as the San Francisco Giants beat the Cubs 4 games to 1.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson's .507 career slugging percentage with the Cubs is fourth highest in team history.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In October 1992 the Red Sox signed Dawson as a free agent.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson hit his 400th career home run with the Red Sox on April 15 at Fenway Park.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson sustained a knee injury early in the 1993 season in a game against the Texas Rangers which limited him to only 121 games in his first year with the Red Sox: "I got caught between sliding and standing up on a passed ball.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] I was on second base, and I took a chop step between strides and hit the corner of the third-base bag.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson would have knee surgery the following year as well, and only managed to play 75 games in his second and final season with Boston.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson played his last two years with the Florida Marlins in Miami, where he was born and raised.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] During the 1995 season, he became an unexpected regular starter, despite his age and history with injuries, due to an injury to outfielder Gary Sheffield.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He played somewhat sparingly with the team the following year, retiring after the 1996 season.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In his final game, Dawson was removed from the field as a final farewell to the fans and the game.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] The fans gave him a standing ovation as Dawson walked off the field.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson finished his career with 2,774 hits, 438 home runs, 314 stolen bases, and 1,591 RBI.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He is one of only eight players in major league history to record over 300 home runs and 300 stolen bases in his career (300-300 club); the other players to accomplish this are Barry Bonds, Willie Mays, Bobby Bonds, Reggie Sanders, Steve Finley, Alex Rodriguez and Carlos Beltrán.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson is also one of only five members of the 400 HR-300 SB club, along with Barry Bonds, Willie Mays, Alex Rodriguez, and Carlos Beltrán.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 1997, Dawson's #10 was retired by the Montreal Expos in his honor (the number had been previously retired for Rusty Staub).
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] After the franchise moved to Washington, the Montreal Canadiens raised a banner in the Bell Centre to commemorate all of the retired Expos numbers, including Dawson's.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 2010 the Washington Nationals franchise placed Dawson in its "Ring of Honor" at Nationals Park.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 2019, Dawson was inducted into the National College Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2010, his ninth year of eligibility, rising from an initial vote total of 45.3% in 2002 to 77.9% in 2010.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Cubs teammate Ryne Sandberg campaigned for Dawson's induction during his speech at his own Hall of Fame induction ceremony in 2005: "No player in baseball history worked harder, suffered more or did it better than Andre Dawson.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] I watched him win an MVP for a last-place team in 1987 [with the Cubs], and it was the most unbelievable thing I've ever seen in baseball.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson's Hall of Fame plaque originally depicted him with a Montreal Expos cap.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson was the second player in the Hall of Fame whose plaque depicted him with an Expos logo, after Gary Carter.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Though Dawson had played most of his 21-year career with Montreal, he publicly expressed his disappointment with the decision, saying it was "a little gut-wrenching" to find out he would not go in as a Chicago Cub.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In late 2023, Dawson sent a letter to the Hall of Fame again requesting that the cap on his plaque be changed to a Cubs hat.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In 2026, the Hall of Fame agreed to recast his plaque with no team logo.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] While Dawson played only six years with the Cubs, five of his eight All-Star appearances were as a Cub, and his only MVP award came in his first year with the team in 1987.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] The Hall noted that "Dawson had 1,575 of his 2,774 hits as an Expo, won six of his eight Gold Glove awards in Montreal and led the Expos to their only postseason series win," the 1981 NLDS win that was also the only postseason win in Dawson's career.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson married the former Vanessa Turner and had two children, Darius in August 1989 and Amber in September 1990.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Shortly after retiring as a player, Dawson returned to the Marlins to accept a position in the team's front office, where he got his first World Series ring in 2003.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson owns the Paradise Memorial Funeral Home in Richmond Heights, Florida.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] He entered the funeral business in 2003, investing in a funeral home his younger brother owned, and became the owner and operator of Paradise Memorial in 2008.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] In an April 2020 Associated Press story on how he and his business dealt with the COVID-19 pandemic, he said, "It’s very sad.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Because people mourn and grieve differently, and they’re not getting through that process as they would under normal circumstances.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] You see a lot of hurt and pain." At that time, his wife Vanessa was the office manager, while an uncle ran day-to-day operations.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson also owned The Mahogany Grille, a soul food restaurant in Miami Gardens, Florida.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson has regularly attended Chicago Cubs functions since his retirement and is a fan favorite.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson appeared in a 2012 "Discount Double-Check" commercial for State Farm Insurance with former Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Dawson released his autobiography, *If You Love This Game: An MVP's Life in Baseball*, in May 2012.
[src:center-fielder/andre-dawson] Though Dawson batted and threw right-handed, he writes with his left hand.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones made his MLB debut during the 1996 season with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the 1996 World Series, he became the youngest player ever to hit a home run in the postseason, and just the second player ever to homer in his first two World Series at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The following season, he finished fifth in voting for Rookie of the Year.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He continued to improve his offensive production the next two seasons, and in 2000, he batted .303 with 36 home runs and 104 runs batted in (RBIs), making his first All-Star team.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones started to draw many comparisons to Willie Mays and was considered one of the top center fielders in baseball.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He proved to be a top defensive player, leading all center fielders in putouts and total zone runs five years in a row from 1998 to 2002.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2001, he again hit more than 30 home runs and drove in 104 runs but his average dipped to .251 while his strikeouts increased.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones improved with All-Star seasons in 2002 and 2003.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2004, he failed to hit at least 30 home runs for the first time since 1999 and exceeded 100 strikeouts, which became a regular occurrence thereafter.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2005, he led the National League (NL) with 51 home runs and 128 RBIs, finishing second to Albert Pujols for NL Most Valuable Player.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In subsequent seasons, his average continued to dip and his strikeouts increased.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After a productive season in 2006, including a career-high 129 RBIs, in 2007 Jones had his weakest season to that point, batting just .222.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] During his time with Atlanta, Jones became one of the youngest players in MLB history to reach 300 career home runs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After the 2007 season, Jones signed with the Dodgers as a free agent to a two-year deal, worth $36.2 million.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, Jones struggled with the Dodgers, batting just .158 with three home runs and 14 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Shortly after the season, Jones was released.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones concluded his MLB career with brief stints for the Rangers, White Sox, and Yankees, transitioning from a starting center fielder to designated hitter and backup outfielder role.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones hit his 400th career home run in 2010 while playing for the White Sox.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2026, Jones will be inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He became the first Curaçaoan player to be elected into the Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was born on April 23, 1977, in Willemstad, Curaçao.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] By the age of 11, Jones was on a youth select baseball team that traveled to Japan to play in a tournament.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He could handle any position on the field, but because of his powerful arm, Jones often found himself at catcher or third base.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He switched to the outfield a couple of years later.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones signed with the Atlanta Braves organization as a free agent in 1993 at the age of 16.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was promoted to Danville of the Appalachian League after only 27 games with the Gulf Coast League Braves.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He finished the season with 25 home runs and 100 runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones also led the South Atlantic League with 56 steals.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His outstanding season was capped off when he was named minor league player of the year by *USA Today* and *Baseball America*.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The Braves brought Jones up to Atlanta on August 15, 1996, when he was just 19 years old.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In his first career major league game, Jones went 1-for-5 with a run batted in and a run scored.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In his second game, he went 2-for-5 with a home run and a triple.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He had his first multi-homer game against the Reds on August 22.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He spent his early time in the majors playing in right field because established center fielder Marquis Grissom was already entrenched in the position.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He finished the season batting .217 with five home runs and 13 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the National League Championship Series against the Cardinals, Jones batted .222 with a home run and 3 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The Braves won the Series and advanced to the World Series.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In Game 1 of the 1996 World Series on October 20, Jones was able to demonstrate his talents on the national stage.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He connected for two home runs to left field on his first two at bats as the Braves routed the New York Yankees 12–1.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones became the youngest player ever to homer in the World Series at the age of 19 years, 180 days, breaking Mickey Mantle's record of 20 years, 362 days — on what would have been Mantle's 65th birthday.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones joined Gene Tenace as the only other player to hit home runs in his first two World Series at bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Tenace did it in 1972 with the Oakland Athletics.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones became the Braves' everyday right fielder in 1997.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones hit his first home run of the season against Jeff McCurry of the Rockies.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones had his second multi-homer game against the Cubs on July 22.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On August 31, Jones went 3-for-3 with a home run and five runs batted in a game against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished his rookie season with a .231 batting average, 18 home runs, and 70 runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones also showed his speed by stealing 20 bases.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He finished fifth in Rookie of the Year voting.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 1998, he moved to center field nearly full-time and had a much more encouraging season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He hit his 30th home run of the season against Florida on September 13.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He also won his first of ten consecutive Gold Glove Awards.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the National League Division Series, Jones went 0-for-9 but drew 3 walks.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The Braves won the series against the Cubs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the 1998 NLCS against the San Diego Padres, Jones batted .273 with a home run and two RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, The Braves lost the series in six games.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Whether he was in the batter's box or gliding under a fly ball to make an easy basket catch, Jones played the game in a very relaxed manner.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] This temporarily earned him the ire of manager Bobby Cox in June 1998 in an incident in which Cox pulled Jones out of a game, in the midst of an inning, because he felt Jones had lazily allowed a single to drop in center field.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones went on to hit .271 with 31 home runs and 90 runs batted in and stole 27 bases.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Still just 22 years old, Jones had similar numbers in 1999.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He had a breakout season with his bat in 2000 with career highs up until that point in batting average (.303), home runs (36), and RBIs (104).
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He also earned his first All-Star Game appearance.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He also led the National League in Plate Appearances (729) and At Bats (656).
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones struggled in the National League Division Series against the Cardinals.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, in 2001, Jones' batting average fell and his strikeouts went up.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished with 34 home runs and 104 RBIs but his average dropped to only .251 and he struck out 142 times.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] By now, Jones had gained nearly 30 pounds since arriving in the Major Leagues, greatly diminishing his speed on the basepaths (he would not steal more than 11 bases after 2001).
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He maintained a similar batting performance in 2002, but was still playing superb defense.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On September 7, he belted two home runs in his last two at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In his first two at-bats on September 10, he belted two more home runs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He became the 11th player in MLB history to homer in four straight at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Then on September 25, Jones belted three home runs against the Phillies.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones became the first Braves player to hit three home runs in a game since Jeff Blauser did it in 1992.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was named to his second All Star team.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He ended the season with 35 home runs and 94 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2003, with the power-hitting Gary Sheffield in the line-up, Jones achieved a new career high-water mark in RBIs, with 116.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones made his third All Star team and homered in the game.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The American League beat the National League, 7–6.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the 2004 season, he took a step backward when he hit fewer than 30 homers and struck out 147 times.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] During the season, Jones was the subject of trade rumors.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Prior to the 2005 season, Jones increased his workout regimen and followed advice given by Willie Mays to widen his batting stance.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The result was his most productive offensive season ever.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After Chipper Jones went down with an injury early in 2005, Jones carried the Braves.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] By the All Star break, Jones was leading the National League in home runs with 27.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was named to the All Star team, the fourth of his career.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones hit his 40th home run of the season on August 23 in a loss against the Cubs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] It marked the first time in his career that he hit at least 40 home runs in a season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones became the first Braves hitter to hit 40 home runs in a season since Javy Lopez did it in 2003.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On September 14, 2005, Jones hit his 300th career home run which went 430 feet (130 m) off Philadelphia Phillies reliever Geoff Geary in a 12–4 Phillies win.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The ball landed in the upper deck in left field at Citizens Bank Park.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones became the first hitter since Alex Rodriguez (57) and Jim Thome (52) to hit at least 50 home runs in a season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones also became the 12th player in history to hit 300 home runs before his 30th birthday.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones hit a major league-leading 51 home runs, surpassing Hank Aaron's and Eddie Mathews' single-season club record, and winning the Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He also led the National League with a career-high 128 RBI.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones' torrid hitting in the summer, especially while teammate Chipper Jones was out with an injury, helped carry the Braves to their 14th consecutive division championship.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Louis Cardinals first baseman Albert Pujols in the 2005 NL MVP vote.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In the 2005, National League Divisional Series against the Houston Astros, Jones hit .471 with a home run and five RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, the Astros took the series, 3–1.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Before the 2006 season, Jones played in the World Baseball Classic for the Netherlands.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones started the season by hitting a home run off a pitch from Derek Lowe.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the game by going 2 for 4 with a home run, 4 runs batted in, a strikeout, and a base on balls.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] From April 16 through April 19, Jones homered in 4 consecutive games.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] During that stretch, he batted .438 with 5 home runs and 8 runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the month of April with a .281 average, 8 home runs and 23 runs batted in (RBI).
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones matched his career high with 6 runs batted in on July 18 against the Cardinals.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On August 29, in a game against the Giants, Jones drove in 3 runs, which gave him his 1000th career RBI.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On September 26, in a game against the New York Mets, Jones hit his 40th home run of the season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He became the first hitter in Atlanta's history to have consecutive seasons of at least 40 homers.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the 2006 season with 41 home runs and 129 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones also became more selective at the plate (82 walks, as compared to 64 the prior season), which helped him score 107 runs during 2006, an increase of 12 over the prior year and his most in a single season since 2000.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He won his ninth consecutive Gold Glove award.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] The Braves finished with a 79–83 record and missed the postseason for the first time since 1990.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Coming into the last year of his contract with the Braves, many fans and sports analysts alike felt that 2007 would be his last year as a Brave, mostly because of his potential value on the market that the Braves would not be able to afford.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones, however, had an unexpectedly poor start to the season, striking out 51 times in 41 games and carrying a batting average in the low .200s for the majority of April and May.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On April 30, Jones hit a three-run walk-off home run against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On May 28, Jones hit his 350th career homer off Chris Capuano.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After the All-Star break, Jones continued to have productive power numbers; however, his batting average remained poor.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He was honored with a Fielding Bible Award as the best fielding center fielder in MLB.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the 2007 season with 26 home runs and 94 RBIs.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On the downside, Jones hit only .222 and struck out 138 times.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On October 2, the Braves announced they would not be bringing Jones back for the 2008 season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On December 5, 2007, Jones agreed to a two-year deal with the Los Angeles Dodgers, worth $36.2 million.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After showing up to spring training out of shape and overweight, he continued to struggle, hitting below .200 for most of the season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Additionally, he had only 10 hits in 116 at-bats with runners in scoring position.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Due to his lack of production, Jones was dropped to eighth in the Dodger lineup.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] This was the first time since 1998 that Jones had hit eighth in any lineup.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was put on the disabled list for the first time in his entire career on May 25, 2008.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He had knee surgery after injuring his knee during batting practice earlier that day.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On July 27, Dodgers manager Joe Torre benched Jones and said that he would only be used as a spot starter in the future.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] At that time, Jones had a .166 batting average, two home runs, 12 RBIs, and 68 strikeouts in 187 at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On September 13, 2008, Jones was put on the 60-day disabled list, ending his season with the Dodgers.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the season with a .158 batting average, just three home runs, and 14 RBI.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones stated that he did not wish to return to the Dodgers in 2009, saying that the Los Angeles fans did not give him a fair chance.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] During the off-season, the Dodgers reached an agreement with Jones to trade or release him before spring training in exchange for a deferral of some of the remaining money due on his contract.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On January 15, 2009, Jones was officially released by the Dodgers.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On February 8, 2009, Jones signed a one-year minor league contract with the Texas Rangers; the deal paid him $500,000 for making the major league team, and offered $1 million in incentives.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones reportedly turned down a similar offer from the New York Yankees to compete for their center field job and expressed an interest in staying with the Rangers even though he would likely not be a starter.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He earned the Rangers' final roster spot.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He was originally intended to be a pinch-hitter for the Rangers, but found a starting outfield role due to an injury to Josh Hamilton.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones would go 3-for-5 in his Rangers debut with an RBI and two runs scored.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] By the end of April, Jones was batting .344 with three home runs and six runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was also faced with an opportunity to play against his old club, the Dodgers.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones played two games against them on June 13 and 14, homering in each game.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On July 4, Jones went 2 for 5 with a home run and 4 runs batted in against the Rays.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On July 8, in a game against the Angels, Jones hit three home runs and drove in four runs in an 8–1 win.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] It was his second career three-homer game.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones had a chance to hit his fourth home run of the game in his final two at-bats, but he popped out and struck out.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] "I'm just happy we won." Jones ultimately hit only .214 for the season, but did have 17 home runs in 82 games.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On November 25, 2009, Jones signed a $500,000 deal for 2010 with up to an additional $1 million in performance bonuses.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Unlike what he had done with the Braves and Dodgers in previous seasons, Jones showed up to camp in shape, a full 30 pounds under his previous weight.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On April 23, 2010, Jones hit two home runs on his 33rd birthday, including a walk-off to help the White Sox win 7–6 over the Seattle Mariners.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On July 11, he hit his 400th career home run.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He finished the year with nineteen home runs in 278 at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He scored 41 runs, had 48 RBI and 64 base hits in 107 games, the most games he appeared in since 2007.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On January 20, 2011, Jones and the New York Yankees agreed to a contract for the 2011 season for $2 million, with an additional $1.2 million in performance bonuses.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In his first Yankees at-bat on April 5, he hit a home run over the left field wall at Yankee Stadium off the Minnesota Twins' Brian Duensing.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones finished the season with a .247 average, 13 home runs and 33 runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He became a free agent after the season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones re-signed with the Yankees on December 30, 2011, signing a one-year deal worth $2 million.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, due to Brett Gardner's DL stint, Jones received more starts than anticipated.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones played very well in the first half of the season, hitting 12 home runs in his first 62 games, including three over the course of a doubleheader in Boston, but in August and September, he hit only .139 with two home runs over his final 32 games.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On December 7, 2012, Jones agreed to a one-year, ¥300 million (approximately $3.5 million) contract with the Tohoku Rakuten Golden Eagles of Nippon Professional Baseball.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He finished the regular season with 26 home runs in 478 at-bats.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He scored 81 runs, had 94 RBI, 116 base hits and 105 walks in 143 games, helping Eagles to clinch their first Pacific League Championship.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His steady performance continued in postseason, including two home runs in the Pacific League Climax Series and one in the Japan Series respectively, which played a key role in the Eagles' Japan Series win.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After the season, Jones re-signed with Rakuten for the 2014 season, agreeing to a one-year contract worth ¥400 million (approximately $3.8 million).
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In his two years with Rakuten, Jones hit 50 home runs and played primarily at designated hitter, however he played 48 games at first base, far more than the eight he played in his career before coming to Japan.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] After playing in Japan, Jones attempted comebacks in both the 2015 and 2016 MLB seasons.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He officially retired from baseball in February 2016 and was hired by the Braves as a special assistant later that month.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] On April 3, 2023, the Braves announced that Jones's number 25 would be retired by the team on September 9.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones ended his career with a .254/.337/.486 slash line, along with 434 home runs and 1,289 runs batted in.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His home run total was tied for 40th on the all-time home run list when he ended his career.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, Jones' weakness was hitting against breaking balls and hitting for good average.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Only once in his career did Jones bat .300 or better (he batted .303 in 2000), and he hit just .214 in the final six seasons of his career.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was also known for his speed early in his career.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In fact, his speed earned him the last playoff spot on the Braves' roster in 1996.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones stole 20 or more bases from 1997 to 2000.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] However, his speed declined as he hit for more power.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones never stole 10 bases after he stole 11 in 2001.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] This could also be attributed to a noticeable weight gain.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones also owned the lowest batting average (since broken by Jose Bautista in 2010), slugging percentage, on-base percentage (OBP), and runs scored in a season for a hitter that belted 50+ home runs in a season.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones hit 51 in 2005 but batted just .263, with a .575 slugging percentage, .347 OBP, and 95 runs scored.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] From 1998 to 2007, Jones won 10 consecutive Gold Gloves.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His 10 Gold Gloves for an outfielder ranks him in a tie for third (behind Willie Mays and Roberto Clemente each with 12) with Al Kaline, Ichiro Suzuki, and Ken Griffey Jr. for most Gold Gloves won by an outfielder.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones is also one of five center fielders to record at least 400 putouts in a season six times; the others are Willie Mays, Richie Ashburn, Kirby Puckett, and Max Carey.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones has been ranked by Fangraphs as the most valuable defensive outfielder in baseball history.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Being born in Curaçao, then part of the Netherlands Antilles, Jones represented the Netherlands national baseball team in international competition.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] During the inaugural World Baseball Classic (WBC) in 2006, Jones went hitless in six at-bats, with two walks and two strikeouts.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones returned to the team for the 2013 WBC.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His 2013 was much more successful, as he slashed .333/.441/.370 with nine hits and five walks, leading the team in OBP.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Two years later, in 2015, Jones was selected to play with the national team as a first baseman for the 2015 Premier12.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Over five games, he hit .250, with four hits and two RBI.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones later announced that those were his final games as a player.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was named the manager of the Netherlands national team for the 2026 World Baseball Classic, which took place in Miami in March 2026.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In July 2001, Jones testified in the federal trial of Steve Kaplan, an Atlanta club owner charged with facilitating prostitution.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones testified that he was a regular at the club and that, on one occasion, Kaplan arranged for a limousine to bring him to a hotel where he had sex with a group of people.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He further testified that he made no payment during the encounter because Kaplan had told him that it was a party.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] They are the parents of one son and one daughter.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Son Druw was a top prospect in the 2022 MLB draft and was selected second overall by the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Early on the morning of Christmas, December 25, 2012, Jones was arrested for battery after police officers responded to a domestic disturbance call between him and his wife Nicole in Duluth, Georgia, near Atlanta.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] A police report said Jones allegedly put his hands around her neck and threatened to kill her.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] He was released on $2,400 bond late that morning.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Nicole Jones filed for divorce in early January 2013.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His wife later withdrew the action for divorce and the couple attempted to reconcile, though Jones eventually pleaded guilty, paid a fine, and was placed on probation.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones and his wife supported Jaden's Ladder, a nonprofit organization that assists survivors of domestic violence.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones has appeared on balloting for the National Baseball Hall of Fame since 2018, when he received 7.3% of the vote, well short of the 75% required for election, but above the 5% minimum required to remain on the ballot.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His support has increased to 33.9% as of the 2021 Hall of Fame ballot, his fourth appearance.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His support grew even stronger on the 2022 ballot, reaching up to 41.4% in his 5th year of eligibility and later 58.1% in his 6th year of eligibility in the 2023 ballot and 61.6% in 2024 and 66.2% in 2025.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] In 2026, in his 9th year of eligibility, Jones was elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame by securing 78.4% of the vote, surpassing the 75% required for induction.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] Jones was inducted into the Atlanta Braves Hall of Fame in 2016.
[src:center-fielder/andruw-jones] His uniform number, 25, was retired by the team on September 9, 2023.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:center-fielder/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:center-fielder/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:center-fielder/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:center-fielder/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:center-fielder/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The **National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum** is a history museum and hall of fame in Cooperstown, New York, operated by a private foundation.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] It serves as the central collection and gathering space for the history of baseball in the United States displaying baseball-related artifacts and exhibits, honoring those who have excelled in playing, managing, and serving the sport.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall's motto is "Preserving History, Honoring Excellence, Connecting Generations".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] **Cooperstown** is often used as shorthand (or a metonym) for the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The museum also established and manages the process for honorees into the Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall of Fame was established in 1939 by Stephen Carlton Clark, heir to the Singer Sewing Machine fortune.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Clark sought to bring tourists to the village greatly decimated by the Great Depression, which reduced the local tourist trade, and Prohibition, which devastated the local hops industry.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Clark constructed the Hall of Fame's building, which was dedicated on June 12, 1939.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] (His granddaughter, Jane Forbes Clark, is the current chairman of the board of directors.) The mythology that future Civil War hero Abner Doubleday invented baseball in Cooperstown in the 1830s was instrumental in the placement and early marketing of the Hall.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] An expanded library and research facility opened in 1994.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 2002, the Hall launched *Baseball as America*, a traveling exhibit that toured ten American museums over six years.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall of Fame has since also sponsored educational programming on the Internet to bring the Hall of Fame to schoolchildren who might not visit.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall and Museum completed a series of renovations in spring 2005.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall of Fame also presents an annual exhibit at FanFest at the Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Among baseball fans, "Hall of Fame" means not only the museum and facility in Cooperstown, New York, but the pantheon of players, managers, umpires, executives, and pioneers who have been inducted into the Hall.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The first five men elected were Ty Cobb, Babe Ruth, Honus Wagner, Christy Mathewson and Walter Johnson, chosen in 1936; roughly 20 more were selected before the entire group was inducted at the Hall's 1939 opening.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] As of January 2026, 354 people had been elected to the Hall of Fame, including 281 former professional players, 23 managers, 10 umpires, and 40 pioneers, executives, and organizers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] 119 members of the Hall of Fame have been inducted posthumously, including four who died after their selection was announced.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Of the 39 members primarily recognized for their contributions to Negro league baseball, 31 were inducted posthumously, including all 26 selected since the 1990s.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall of Fame includes one woman, baseball executive Effa Manley.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The newest members of the Hall of Fame as of January 20, 2026, are Carlos Beltrán, Andruw Jones, and Jeff Kent.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 2019, former Yankees closer Mariano Rivera became the first player to be elected unanimously on the writers' ballot.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Derek Jeter, Marvin Miller, Ted Simmons, and Larry Walker were to be inducted in 2020, but their induction ceremony was delayed by the COVID-19 pandemic until September 8, 2021.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The ceremony was open to the public, as COVID restrictions had been lifted.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Players are currently inducted into the Hall of Fame through election by either the Baseball Writers' Association of America (or BBWAA), or the Veterans Committee, which now consists of four subcommittees, each of which considers and votes for candidates from a separate era of baseball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] From a final ballot typically including 25–40 candidates, each writer may vote for up to 10 players; until the late 1950s, voters were advised to cast votes for the maximum 10 candidates.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Any player named on 75% or more of all ballots cast is elected.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A player who is named on fewer than 5% of ballots is dropped from future elections.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In some instances, the screening committee had restored their names to later ballots, but in the mid-1990s, dropped players were made permanently ineligible for Hall of Fame consideration, even by the Veterans Committee.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A 2001 change in the election procedures restored the eligibility of these dropped players; while their names will not appear on future BBWAA ballots, they may be considered by the Veterans Committee.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Players receiving 5% or more of the votes but fewer than 75% are reconsidered annually until a maximum of ten years of eligibility (lowered from fifteen years for the 2015 election).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Under special circumstances, certain players may be deemed eligible for induction even though they have not met all requirements.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Addie Joss was elected in 1978, despite only playing nine seasons before he died of meningitis.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Additionally, if an otherwise eligible player dies before his fifth year of retirement, then that player may be placed on the ballot at the first election at least six months after his death.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Roberto Clemente set the precedent: the writers put him up for consideration after his death on New Year's Eve, 1972, and he was inducted in 1973.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The five-year waiting period was established in 1954 after an evolutionary process.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 1936 all players were eligible, including active ones.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] From the 1937 election until the 1945 election, there was no waiting period, so any retired player was eligible, but writers were discouraged from voting for current major leaguers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Since there was no formal rule preventing a writer from casting a ballot for an active player, the scribes did not always comply with the informal guideline; Joe DiMaggio received a vote in 1945, for example.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] From the 1946 election until the 1954 election, an official one-year waiting period was in effect.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] However, the BBWAA decided to hold a special election at the 1939 Winter Meetings in Cincinnati, specifically to elect Gehrig (most likely because it was known that he was terminally ill, making it uncertain that he would live long enough to see another election).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Nobody else was on that ballot, and the numerical results have never been made public.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Since no elections were held in 1940 or 1941, the special election permitted Gehrig to enter the Hall while still alive.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] If a player fails to be elected by the BBWAA within 10 years of his eligibility for election, he may be selected by the Veterans Committee.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Following changes to the election process for that body made in 2010 and 2016, the Veterans Committee is now responsible for electing all otherwise eligible candidates who are not eligible for the BBWAA ballot — both long-retired players and non-playing personnel (managers, umpires, and executives).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] From 2011 to 2016, each candidate could be considered once every three years; now, the frequency depends on the era in which an individual made his greatest contributions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A more complete discussion of the new process is available below.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] From 2008 to 2010, following changes made by the Hall in July 2007, the main Veterans Committee, then made up of living Hall of Famers, voted only on players whose careers began in 1943 or later.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Players of the Negro leagues have also been considered at various times, beginning in 1971.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Predictably, the selection process catalyzes endless debate among baseball fans over the merits of various candidates.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Even players elected years ago remain the subjects of discussions as to whether they deserved election.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] For example, Bill James' 1994 book *Whatever Happened to the Hall of Fame?* goes into detail about who he believes does and does not belong in the Hall of Fame.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The selection rules for the Baseball Hall of Fame were modified to prevent the induction of anyone on Baseball's "permanently ineligible" list.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Until they were removed from the list in 2025 the most prominent former players to be affected were Pete Rose and "Shoeless Joe" Jackson—many others have been barred from participation in MLB, but none have Hall of Fame qualifications on the level of Jackson or Rose.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Jackson and Rose were both banned from MLB for life for actions related to gambling on games involving their own teams.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Jackson was determined to have cooperated with those who conspired to intentionally lose the 1919 World Series, and for accepting payment for losing, although his actual level of culpability is fiercely debated.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The ensuing Black Sox Scandal led directly to baseball's Rule 21, prominently posted in every clubhouse locker room, which mandates permanent banishment from MLB for having a gambling interest of any sort on a game in which a player, manager or umpire is directly involved.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Rose voluntarily accepted a permanent spot on the ineligible list in return for MLB's promise to make no official finding in relation to alleged betting on the Cincinnati Reds when he was their manager in the 1980s.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] No credible evidence has ever emerged to support allegations that Rose bet against his team and/or that his betting influenced his managerial decisions, nevertheless, the betting constituted a clear violation of the aforementioned Rule 21.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] After years of denial, Rose admitted that he bet on the Reds in his 2004 autobiography *My Prison Without Bars*.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Before the ban was lifted in 2025, baseball fans were deeply split on the issue of whether Rose and/or Jackson (both deceased) should remain banned or have their punishments posthumously revoked.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Writer Bill James, though he advocates Rose eventually making it into the Hall of Fame, compared the people who want to put Jackson in the Hall of Fame to "those women who show up at murder trials wanting to marry the cute murderer".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The actions and composition of the Veterans Committee have been at times controversial, with occasional selections of contemporaries and teammates of the committee members over seemingly more worthy candidates.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 2001, the Veterans Committee was reformed to comprise the living Hall of Fame members and other honorees.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The revamped Committee held three elections, in 2003 and 2007, for both players and non-players, and in 2005 for players only.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] No individual was elected in that time, sparking criticism among some observers who expressed doubt whether the new Veterans Committee would ever elect a player.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Committee members, most of whom were Hall members, were accused of being reluctant to elect new candidates in the hope of heightening the value of their own selection.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] After no one was selected for the third consecutive election in 2007, Hall of Famer Mike Schmidt noted, "The same thing happens every year.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Separate committees, including sportswriters and broadcasters, would select umpires, managers and executives, as well as players from earlier eras.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In the first election to be held under the 2007 revisions, two managers and three executives were elected in December 2007 as part of the 2008 election process.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The next Veterans Committee elections for players were held in December 2008 as part of the 2009 election process; the main committee did not select a player, while the panel for pre–World War II players elected Joe Gordon in its first and ultimately only vote.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The main committee voted as part of the election process for inductions in odd-numbered years, while the pre-World War II panel would vote every five years, and the panel for umpires, managers, and executives voted as part of the election process for inductions in even-numbered years.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Further changes to the Veterans Committee process were announced by the Hall in July 2010, July 2016, and April 2022.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A one-year waiting period beyond potential BBWAA eligibility (which had been abolished in 2016) was reintroduced, thus restricting the committee to considering players retired for at least 16 seasons.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The eligibility criteria for Era Committee consideration differ between players, managers, and executives.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] While the text on a player's or manager's plaque lists all teams for which the inductee was a member in that specific role, inductees are usually depicted wearing the cap of a specific team, though in a few cases, like umpires, they wear caps without logos.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] (Executives are not depicted wearing caps.) Additionally, as of 2015, inductee biographies on the Hall's website for all players and managers, and executives who were associated with specific teams, list a "primary team", which does not necessarily match the cap logo.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Although the Hall always made the final decision on which logo was shown, until 2001 the Hall deferred to the wishes of players or managers whose careers were linked with multiple teams.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In all of the above cases, the "primary team" is the team for which the inductee spent the largest portion of his career except for Ryan, whose primary team is listed as the Angels despite playing one fewer season for that team than for the Astros.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 2001, the Hall of Fame decided to change the policy on cap logo selection, as a result of rumors that some teams were offering compensation, such as number retirement, money, or organizational jobs, in exchange for the cap designation.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A further update to the cap policy was introduced in 2018 that stated that the Hall of Fame would no longer make plaques for former Cleveland Indians players with them wearing the Chief Wahoo logo.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] This came after former Indians player Jim Thome specifically requested not to have Chief Wahoo on his plaque.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Existing exhibits and plaques with the logo would remain in place.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 1934, the idea for establishing a Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum was devised by several individuals, such as Ford C.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Frick (president of the National League) and Alexander Cleland, a Scottish immigrant who decided to serve as the first executive secretary for the Museum for the next seven years that worked with the interests of the Village and Major League Baseball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Stephen Carlton Clark (a Cooperstown native) paid for the construction of the museum, which was planned to open in 1939 to mark the "Centennial of Baseball", which included renovations to Doubleday Field.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] William Beattie served as the first curator of the museum.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] According to the Hall of Fame, approximately 260,000 visitors enter the museum each year, and the running total has surpassed 17 million.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] These visitors see only a fraction of its 40,000 artifacts, 3 million library items (such as newspaper clippings and photos) and 140,000 baseball cards.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall has seen a noticeable decrease in attendance since the mid-2010s.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A 2013 story on ESPN.com about the village of Cooperstown and its relation to the game partially linked the reduced attendance with Cooperstown Dreams Park, a youth baseball complex about 5 miles (8.0 km) away in the town of Hartwick.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The 22 fields at Dreams Park currently draw 17,000 players each summer for a week of intensive play; while the complex includes housing for the players, their parents and grandparents must stay elsewhere.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] A controversy erupted in 1982, when it emerged that some historic items given to the Hall had been sold on the collectibles market.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Under pressure from the New York Attorney General, the Commissioner's Office made reparations, but the negative publicity damaged the Hall of Fame's reputation, and made it more difficult for it to solicit donations.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] In 2012, Congress passed and President Barack Obama signed a law ordering the United States Mint to produce and sell commemorative, non-circulating coins to benefit the private, non-profit Hall.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] 2527, was introduced in the United States House of Representatives by Rep.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] Richard Hanna, a Republican from New York, and passed the House on October 26, 2011.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The coins, which depict baseball gloves and balls, are the first concave designs produced by the Mint.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The mintage included 50,000 gold coins, 400,000 silver coins, and 750,000 clad (nickel-copper) coins.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Mint released them on March 27, 2014, and the gold and silver editions quickly sold out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-hall-of-fame] The Hall receives money from surcharges included in the sale price: a total of $9.5 million if all the coins are sold.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:center-fielder/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] A **center fielder**, abbreviated **CF**, is the outfielder in baseball who plays defense in **center field** – the baseball and softball fielding position between left field and right field.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the center fielder is assigned the number 8.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] Outfielders must cover large distances, so speed, instincts and quickness to react to the ball are key.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] They must be able to catch fly balls above their heads and on the run.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] They must be able to throw the ball accurately over a long distance to be effective.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] As well as the requirements above, the center fielder must be the outfielder who has the best combination of speed and throwing distance.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] The center fielder "covers more 'grass' than any other player" (see photo) and, most likely, will catch the most fly balls.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] The position also has the greatest responsibility among the three outfielders for coordinating their play to prevent collisions when converging on a fly ball, and on plays where the center fielder does not make the catch, he must position himself behind the corner outfielder as backup.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] The center outfielder is the captain of the outfield and has the authority to call off the corner fielders when he has a better chance to catch the ball.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] Aside from requiring more speed and range, the center field position is slightly easier to field because balls tend to fly on a straight path, rather than curving as they do for the other outfield positions.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] A center fielder's vision and depth perception is a coveted skill and must be above average.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] Because the position requires a good arm and fast legs, center field is generally where the team puts its best all-around athletes; as a result, center fielders are often fine hitters as well.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] Many center fielders are renowned as excellent batters and base runners.
[src:center-fielder/center-fielder] When a base runner is trying to steal second base the center fielder must back up second base on throws from the catcher to second base in case the second baseman misses the catch or it is a bad throw.
